  1. Notice that there are some incidents identified as NOT COUNTED. These should be removed from the data because they were either not sharks, unverified, or were provoked. Its OK to replace the sharks object.
sharks <- sharks %>% 
  filter(incident_num != 'NOT COUNTED')

  1. Are there any hotspots for shark incidents in California? Make a table and plot that shows the total number of incidents per county. Which county has the highest number of incidents?
sharks %>% 
  group_by(county) %>% 
  count() %>% 
  arrange(-n)

San Diego has the highest number of shark incidents.

sharks %>% 
  group_by(county) %>% 
  count() %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x=reorder(county, n), y=n))+ geom_col()+
  coord_flip()+
  labs(title='Shark Incidents in California', x='County', y='Number of Incidents')+
  theme(plot.title = element_text(size = rel(1.5), hjust = .5))

  1. Are there months of the year when incidents are more likely to occur? Make a table and a plot that shows the total number of incidents by month. Which month has the highest number of incidents?

October had the highest number of shark incidents.

incidents_per_month <- sharks %>% 
  mutate(month = as.factor(month)) %>% 
  group_by(month) %>% 
  summarize(num_of_incidents=n_distinct(incident_num)) %>% 
  arrange(-num_of_incidents)

  1. How do the number and types of injuries compare by county? Make a table that shows the number of injury types by county. Which county has the highest number incidents? San Diego has the highest number of incidents.
num_of_injuries <- sharks %>%
  group_by(county, injury) %>% 
  count() %>% 
  pivot_wider(names_from = injury, values_from = n) %>% 
  mutate(total=rowSums(across(c(major, minor, none, fatal)), na.rm = TRUE)) %>% 
  arrange(-total)

  1. Use the table from #5 to make a plot that shows the total number of incidents by county.
num_of_injuries %>% 
  pivot_longer(cols = c(major, minor, none, fatal), names_to = 'injury', values_to = 'n') %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x=county, y=n, fill = injury))+ geom_col()+ 
  coord_flip()+
  labs(title='Number of Injury Types by County', x='County', y='Number of Incidents')+
  theme(plot.title = element_text(size = rel(1.5), hjust = 0.5))

  1. In the data, mode refers to a type of activity. Which activity is associated with the highest number of incidents?

Surfing/Boarding is associated with the highest number of incidents.

sharks %>% 
  group_by(mode) %>% 
  summarize(total_mode=n()) %>% 
  arrange(-total_mode)

  theme(plot.title = element_text(size = rel(1.5), hjust = 0.5))

  1. Are all incidents involving Great Whites fatal? Make a plot that shows the number and types of incidents for Great Whites only.
    Not all Great White Shark incidents are fatal, it also involves minor, major, and no injuries.
white_shark_incidents <- sharks %>% 
  filter(species=='White') %>% 
  select(incident_num, species, injury) %>% 
  count(injury)

white_shark_incidents
## # A tibble: 4  2
##   injury     n
##   <chr>  <int>
## 1 fatal     15
## 2 major     59
## 3 minor     31
## 4 none      74
white_shark_incidents %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x=reorder(injury, n), y=n)) + geom_col()+
  labs(title='Incidents Involving Great White Sharks', x='Type of Injury', y='Number of Incidents')+
  theme(plot.title = element_text(size = rel(1.5), hjust = 0.5))
